            {
              "id": "CVE-2026-42584",
              "name": "LanguageSpecificPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "netty: io.netty/netty-codec-http: Netty: Incorrect HTTP response parsing leads to data confusion"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Netty is an asynchronous, event-driven network application framework. Prior to 4.2.13.Final and 4.1.133.Final, HttpClientCodec pairs each inbound response with an outbound request by queue.poll() once per response, including for 1xx. If the client pipelines GET then HEAD and the server sends 103, then 200 with GET body, then 200 for HEAD, the queue pairs HEAD with the first 200. The HEAD rule then skips reading that message’s body, so the GET entity bytes stay on the stream and the following 200 is parsed from the wrong offset. This vulnerability is fixed in 4.2.13.Final and 4.1.133.Final."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-42584",
              "help": {
                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2026-42584\nSeverity: HIGH\nPackage: io.netty:netty-codec-http\nFixed Version: 4.2.13.Final, 4.1.133.Final\nLink: [CVE-2026-42584](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-42584)\nNetty is an asynchronous, event-driven network application framework. Prior to 4.2.13.Final and 4.1.133.Final, HttpClientCodec pairs each inbound response with an outbound request by queue.poll() once per response, including for 1xx. If the client pipelines GET then HEAD and the server sends 103, then 200 with GET body, then 200 for HEAD, the queue pairs HEAD with the first 200. The HEAD rule then skips reading that message’s body, so the GET entity bytes stay on the stream and the following 200 is parsed from the wrong offset. This vulnerability is fixed in 4.2.13.Final and 4.1.133.Final.",
                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2026-42584**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|HIGH|io.netty:netty-codec-http|4.2.13.Final, 4.1.133.Final|[CVE-2026-42584](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-42584)|\n\nNetty is an asynchronous, event-driven network application framework. Prior to 4.2.13.Final and 4.1.133.Final, HttpClientCodec pairs each inbound response with an outbound request by queue.poll() once per response, including for 1xx. If the client pipelines GET then HEAD and the server sends 103, then 200 with GET body, then 200 for HEAD, the queue pairs HEAD with the first 200. The HEAD rule then skips reading that message’s body, so the GET entity bytes stay on the stream and the following 200 is parsed from the wrong offset. This vulnerability is fixed in 4.2.13.Final and 4.1.133.Final."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cvssv3_baseScore": 7.3,
                "cvssv3_vector": "CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:L/I:L/A:L",
                "precision": "very-high",
                "security-severity": "7.3",
                "tags": [
                  "vulnerability",
                  "security",
                  "HIGH"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CVE-2026-42587",
              "name": "LanguageSpecificPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "netty: io.netty/netty-codec-http: io.netty/netty-codec-http2: Netty: Denial of Service via unbounded memory allocation in HTTP content decompression"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Netty is an asynchronous, event-driven network application framework. Prior to 4.2.13.Final and 4.1.133.Final, HttpContentDecompressor accepts a maxAllocation parameter to limit decompression buffer size and prevent decompression bomb attacks. This limit is correctly enforced for gzip and deflate encodings via ZlibDecoder, but is silently ignored when the content encoding is br (Brotli), zstd, or snappy. An attacker can bypass the configured decompression limit by sending a compressed payload with Content-Encoding: br instead of Content-Encoding: gzip, causing unbounded memory allocation and out-of-memory denial of service. The same vulnerability exists in DelegatingDecompressorFrameListener for HTTP/2 connections. This vulnerability is fixed in 4.2.13.Final and 4.1.133.Final."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-42587",
              "help": {
                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2026-42587\nSeverity: HIGH\nPackage: io.netty:netty-codec-http2\nFixed Version: 4.2.13.Final, 4.1.133.Final\nLink: [CVE-2026-42587](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-42587)\nNetty is an asynchronous, event-driven network application framework. Prior to 4.2.13.Final and 4.1.133.Final, HttpContentDecompressor accepts a maxAllocation parameter to limit decompression buffer size and prevent decompression bomb attacks. This limit is correctly enforced for gzip and deflate encodings via ZlibDecoder, but is silently ignored when the content encoding is br (Brotli), zstd, or snappy. An attacker can bypass the configured decompression limit by sending a compressed payload with Content-Encoding: br instead of Content-Encoding: gzip, causing unbounded memory allocation and out-of-memory denial of service. The same vulnerability exists in DelegatingDecompressorFrameListener for HTTP/2 connections. This vulnerability is fixed in 4.2.13.Final and 4.1.133.Final.",
                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2026-42587**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|HIGH|io.netty:netty-codec-http2|4.2.13.Final, 4.1.133.Final|[CVE-2026-42587](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-42587)|\n\nNetty is an asynchronous, event-driven network application framework. Prior to 4.2.13.Final and 4.1.133.Final, HttpContentDecompressor accepts a maxAllocation parameter to limit decompression buffer size and prevent decompression bomb attacks. This limit is correctly enforced for gzip and deflate encodings via ZlibDecoder, but is silently ignored when the content encoding is br (Brotli), zstd, or snappy. An attacker can bypass the configured decompression limit by sending a compressed payload with Content-Encoding: br instead of Content-Encoding: gzip, causing unbounded memory allocation and out-of-memory denial of service. The same vulnerability exists in DelegatingDecompressorFrameListener for HTTP/2 connections. This vulnerability is fixed in 4.2.13.Final and 4.1.133.Final."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cvssv3_baseScore": 7.5,
                "cvssv3_vector": "CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:N/I:N/A:H",
                "precision": "very-high",
                "security-severity": "7.5",
                "tags": [
                  "vulnerability",
                  "security",
                  "HIGH"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CVE-2025-55163",
              "name": "LanguageSpecificPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "netty: netty-codec-http2: Netty MadeYouReset HTTP/2 DDoS Vulnerability"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Netty is an asynchronous, event-driven network application framework. Prior to versions 4.1.124.Final and 4.2.4.Final, Netty is vulnerable to MadeYouReset DDoS. This is a logical vulnerability in the HTTP/2 protocol, that uses malformed HTTP/2 control frames in order to break the max concurrent streams limit - which results in resource exhaustion and distributed denial of service. This issue has been patched in versions 4.1.124.Final and 4.2.4.Final."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-55163",
              "help": {
                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2025-55163\nSeverity: HIGH\nPackage: io.netty:netty-codec-http2\nFixed Version: 4.2.4.Final, 4.1.124.Final\nLink: [CVE-2025-55163](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-55163)\nNetty is an asynchronous, event-driven network application framework. Prior to versions 4.1.124.Final and 4.2.4.Final, Netty is vulnerable to MadeYouReset DDoS. This is a logical vulnerability in the HTTP/2 protocol, that uses malformed HTTP/2 control frames in order to break the max concurrent streams limit - which results in resource exhaustion and distributed denial of service. This issue has been patched in versions 4.1.124.Final and 4.2.4.Final.",
                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2025-55163**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|HIGH|io.netty:netty-codec-http2|4.2.4.Final, 4.1.124.Final|[CVE-2025-55163](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-55163)|\n\nNetty is an asynchronous, event-driven network application framework. Prior to versions 4.1.124.Final and 4.2.4.Final, Netty is vulnerable to MadeYouReset DDoS. This is a logical vulnerability in the HTTP/2 protocol, that uses malformed HTTP/2 control frames in order to break the max concurrent streams limit - which results in resource exhaustion and distributed denial of service. This issue has been patched in versions 4.1.124.Final and 4.2.4.Final."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cvssv3_baseScore": 7.5,
                "cvssv3_vector": "CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:N/I:N/A:H",
                "cvssv40_baseScore": 8.2,
                "cvssv40_vector": "CVSS:4.0/AV:N/AC:L/AT:P/PR:N/UI:N/VC:N/VI:N/VA:H/SC:N/SI:N/SA:N",
                "precision": "very-high",
                "security-severity": "7.5",
                "tags": [
