                  "security",
                  "HIGH"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CVE-2026-33871",
              "name": "LanguageSpecificPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "netty: Netty: Denial of Service via HTTP/2 CONTINUATION frame flood"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Netty is an asynchronous, event-driven network application framework. In versions prior to 4.1.132.Final and 4.2.10.Final, a remote user can trigger a Denial of Service (DoS) against a Netty HTTP/2 server by sending a flood of `CONTINUATION` frames. The server's lack of a limit on the number of `CONTINUATION` frames, combined with a bypass of existing size-based mitigations using zero-byte frames, allows an user to cause excessive CPU consumption with minimal bandwidth, rendering the server unresponsive. Versions 4.1.132.Final and 4.2.10.Final fix the issue."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-33871",
              "help": {
                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2026-33871\nSeverity: HIGH\nPackage: io.netty:netty-codec-http2\nFixed Version: 4.1.132.Final, 4.2.11.Final\nLink: [CVE-2026-33871](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-33871)\nNetty is an asynchronous, event-driven network application framework. In versions prior to 4.1.132.Final and 4.2.10.Final, a remote user can trigger a Denial of Service (DoS) against a Netty HTTP/2 server by sending a flood of `CONTINUATION` frames. The server's lack of a limit on the number of `CONTINUATION` frames, combined with a bypass of existing size-based mitigations using zero-byte frames, allows an user to cause excessive CPU consumption with minimal bandwidth, rendering the server unresponsive. Versions 4.1.132.Final and 4.2.10.Final fix the issue.",
                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2026-33871**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|HIGH|io.netty:netty-codec-http2|4.1.132.Final, 4.2.11.Final|[CVE-2026-33871](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-33871)|\n\nNetty is an asynchronous, event-driven network application framework. In versions prior to 4.1.132.Final and 4.2.10.Final, a remote user can trigger a Denial of Service (DoS) against a Netty HTTP/2 server by sending a flood of `CONTINUATION` frames. The server's lack of a limit on the number of `CONTINUATION` frames, combined with a bypass of existing size-based mitigations using zero-byte frames, allows an user to cause excessive CPU consumption with minimal bandwidth, rendering the server unresponsive. Versions 4.1.132.Final and 4.2.10.Final fix the issue."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cvssv40_baseScore": 8.7,
                "cvssv40_vector": "CVSS:4.0/AV:N/AC:L/AT:N/PR:N/UI:N/VC:N/VI:N/VA:H/SC:N/SI:N/SA:N",
